# Performance

## Applies when

Request this rule when creating, reviewing, or modifying `_process`, `_physics_process`, `_draw`, polling loops, repeated UI refresh, large collections, gameplay logs, rendered log lists, catalog scans, cache layers, profiling code, or performance optimizations. Priority: Medium.

## Source of truth

- `docs/prd/15_GODOT_ARCHITECTURE.md` owns architecture boundaries, UI-to-facade flow, deterministic logic, random ownership, file-size limits, and static scan expectations.
- `docs/prd/17_UI_UX_SPEC.md` owns UI refresh behavior, signal usage, thin UI scripts, preview/selector usage, and UI test expectations.

The project does not currently define a quantitative performance budget. Do not treat `60 FPS`, `16 ms`, frame-time targets, memory ceilings, collection limits, or log limits as PRD invariants unless an owner PRD adds them.

## Measurement first

- Identify the concrete performance concern before optimizing.
- Prefer Godot profiler evidence, targeted timing, reproducible test cases, or static-scan evidence over assumptions.
- If profiling cannot be run, report `not run` with the reason instead of claiming improvement.
- Keep optimizations scoped to the measured bottleneck.
- Do not rewrite gameplay architecture only for speculative performance gains.

## Event-driven UI

- UI should refresh from facade signals, mutator results, selectors, and explicit user selection changes.
- Do not poll gameplay state every frame when a signal or explicit refresh path exists.
- Do not recompute expensive previews every frame; update previews on relevant selection, hover, state, or phase changes.
- `_process`, `_physics_process`, and `_draw` in UI must be presentation-only unless the owner PRD explicitly requires otherwise.
- Per-frame UI code must not mutate gameplay state, consume gameplay random, run AI, advance phases, validate gameplay rules, or append gameplay logs.

## Bounded work

- Avoid unbounded per-frame loops over players, cards, logs, Resources, scenes, or UI nodes.
- Keep rendered UI lists bounded or virtualized where practical without mutating canonical gameplay state.
- Do not prune, truncate, or reorder gameplay logs, history, event payloads, random history, or replay-relevant state unless the owner PRD defines that behavior.
- Prefer owner catalogs/selectors over repeated ad-hoc filesystem loads or full Resource scans.
- Large collections must have a clear owner, invalidation point, and test coverage when behavior is replay-sensitive.

## Caching

- Cache immutable Resources, catalog membership, static formatting helpers, or presentation-only derived data only when there is measured need or an established owner pattern.
- Do not cache mutable runtime state as authoritative gameplay state.
- Do not cache selector/view results across mutators, signals, phase changes, or game restart as if they were current gameplay truth.
- Every cache over derived state must have explicit invalidation tied to state changes, phase changes, setup restart, or owner data reload.
- Do not use caches to bypass validation, selectors, facade APIs, catalogs, or PRD-owned logic.

## Replay and gameplay semantics

- Performance changes must preserve gameplay semantics exactly.
- Do not change deterministic random call order, random step counts, random tags, tie-break behavior, event order, validation order, phase commits, AI choices, or winner resolution for speed.
- Do not move gameplay random into UI, `_process`, `_draw`, background helpers, audio, timers, or local random streams.
- Do not reorder side effects if logs, signals, replay output, tests, or PRD order depend on them.
- After sensitive optimizations touching random, AI, phase flow, combat, market, contracts, contacts, Street Deals, logs, or state commits, run replay/determinism tests or report them as `not run`.

## Forbidden behavior

- Do not declare `60 FPS`, `16 ms`, or any other numeric target a hard PRD invariant without owner PRD authority.
- Do not prematurely cache mutable state, active snapshots, selector results, random state, view models, player dictionaries, card arrays, logs, or validation results.
- Do not change random call order, validation order, event order, or committed state shape for performance.
- Do not hide slow logic behind background timers, deferred calls, hidden auto-actions, or async flows that change gameplay ordering.
- Do not skip validation, static scans, GUT tests, or replay tests to make code faster.
- Do not weaken tests, remove assertions, or loosen exact deterministic expectations as a performance fix.
- Do not add new global managers, event buses, worker systems, object pools, or cache services unless an owner PRD requires them or the user explicitly approves PRD maintenance.

## Required checks

For performance-sensitive changes, verify as relevant:

- Profiler/timing/static evidence exists for the bottleneck or `not run` is reported.
- `_process`, `_physics_process`, and `_draw` do not perform gameplay mutation or random consumption.
- UI refresh remains event-driven and selector/facade-based.
- Large collections and rendered logs have bounded work without truncating canonical gameplay state.
- Caches do not become authoritative gameplay state and have explicit invalidation.
- Deterministic random step counts and replay output remain unchanged.
- Unit, integration, static, and replay tests are run according to the risk of the touched path.

## Output requirements

When implementing or reviewing performance changes, report:

- Owner PRD sections used.
- Performance concern and evidence gathered.
- Files and hot paths changed.
- Whether gameplay semantics, random order, event order, or replay output could be affected.
- Tests and profiling/checks run, including explicit `not run` items with the reason.
